Ever wonder where we get our boba from? If you guessed Taiwan, that’s a pretty good guess! The majority of boba is made and exported out of Taiwan. But we actually make our own at our tapioca ball factory, @usbobaco located in Hayward California! We were the first to start a boba factory here in the United States and since then it has made its way into all of our stores, our boba kits and even other popular cafes across the country. 🧋🙏

We wanted to send a quick shout out to everyone in the @heybyemahjongsociety. We have been holding mahjong parties over the last year and love seeing people play mahjong for the first time. 🀄️

Tbh, we were a little anxious to fold our passion of mahjong into the Boba Guys community. After over a decade of pushing boba into everyday lives, we thought about all the various ways to continue innovating. We entertained doing dessert popups, more apparel, and even a speakeasy concept. After much debate, we landed on the idea of mahjong as our original team used to play mahjong together. And given our voice combines Eastern and Western values, we felt mahjong embodied the spirit of bridging cultures.

There’s a lot more to it as we often layer our projects, but we just wanted to thank you for making the events a fun (and loud clacking) success. We envision a future where everyone plays mahjong as much as everyone drinks boba nowadays. See you at the next event! 加油!

It’s a Black Sesame Latte kind of day. We launched this drink five years ago and it’s been going strong. We based our initial recipe on the black sesame soup (黑芝麻糊) that is traditionally a dessert in East Asian and Southeast Asian cultures. Over the years, we got feedback that it was too heavy as a beverage so we thinned out our recipe a bit.

Our housemade black sesame paste is a combination of the black sesame seed itself along with ginger and some brown sugar. Black sesame is known to improve circulation and provide an anti-oxidant boost.

New for Spring Summer 2023 is our California exclusive: Sapin Sapin. For those that might not know, it’s traditionally a steamed dessert made of glutinous rice flour, coconut milk, sugar, and flavoring. We’ve taken that classic and recreated it in drink form! It's complex with different layers varying in color. The white represents the base flavor of coconut milk. The purple is for ube (purple yam). The yellow is for jackfruit. Finally, we finish it all off with toasted coconut! Have you guys tried Sapin Sapin yet?

Last week, we had our annual retail leadership summit. The theme of 2023 is “First Things First” as we’re continuing to rebuild our systems coming out of the pandemic. We know a lot has changed in many of the communities we serve, so we are slowly pivoting our operations to adjust with the times. 

We usually don’t bore everyone with how we operate but if you are curious, our initiatives roll up into three buckets:
1) Operational Excellence
2) Cultural Impact
3) Financial Performance

A lot of the new ideas like “Build Your Own Frescas” or even how we train our teams came from this annual theme. We also introduced a lot of programming behind the scenes that also ladder up to each of the three buckets. We hope to share more soon! Until then, enjoy a glimpse of our summit.

We’ve got something special this season, only for our LA/OC locations: Drinkable Mochi! 

Mochi is a type of Japanese rice cake that is soft and bouncy and uses glutinous rice, water, and sugar as a base. Traditionally, the rice is pounded into a sticky paste and shaped into a round ball.

Our version (all the rage in Asia right now) is so soft it’s drinkable through a boba straw! We’ve been tinkering on this for quite some time now, let us know what you think of our newest topping! 🍡☁️

Today is #NationalTapiocaDay! Over five years ago, we opened the country’s first (and only) tapioca manufacturing facility @usbobaco . It survived the pandemic, so we are extra grateful to still be rolling and tumbling some balls for you all. We’d like to say we are still the country’s foremost expert on (tapioca) balls. 🤣

Tapioca is the starch of the cassava plant. Cassava historically had been a plant grown in South America before its popularity grew in Southeast Asia, largely for its use in desserts. Tapioca is super versatile— you all know it for boba, but it’s also used in pudding, cakes, and even tempura batter. It’s what gives the chewy (ie QQ) mouthfeel. 

So cheers to tapioca today! 🧋

This week, we celebrate our 12th year at Boba Guys. The original mission statement some of the Day Ones might recall is “taking boba and tea to the next level.” We hope that part of the vision was accomplished. We then evolve the mission into ‘bridging cultures’ as we felt our approach of business was more deep and nuanced than most. Fast forward to 2023, we now have 20+ stores and are slowly regaining our footing after a seeing our industry and communities adjust to the times.

Instead of making a flashy Reel / TikTok, we thought we’d take a slow stroll down memory lane. Internally, we see the last decade in four distinct eras:

1) Startup Era - when we burst onto the scene with #fightthepowder energy and probably pushed the envelope too much. 🤣
2) Purpose and Transparency Era - this little side hustle became a real thing so we had to give this company a vision and North Star. To us, it became bridging cultures where we saw a growing divide among our community: East vs. West, Tech vs. Arts, Team Jacob vs. Team Edward (you might remember our now-cringe Twilight references 🤣).
3) Growth Era - the rocket ship 🚀 that really put us on the map, from bringing Oatly to the States to bamboo straws to lines that stretched across NYC blocks. Lots of mixed feelings about this era. 🤪
4) Run It Back / Recovery Era - in an instant, everything changed… for you, our cities, and for the world. For us, our strongest market (SF) lost its mojo. With our size, we have to play it more conservatively as we now have to navigate a recession after a pandemic.

But this post to let everyone know— especially those who rooted for us for over a decade— we are still here and will continue to push boundaries. We know we aren’t the startup or underdog anymore. In the next year, we are rolling out a lot of exciting initiatives including our take on a loyalty-recognition program. 😬 You might have also noticed we went back to our roots and teamed up with a lot of local businesses. You’ll see a lot more of that. 

We know times are tough for everyone right now, so thank you to each and every one of you (especially our team members) who still rock with us and helped us make culture. 🙏🏼🫡

I’m not asking, I’m telling. 🧋

We launched this drink almost six years ago and it’s been going strong. We based our initial recipe on the black sesame soup (黑芝麻糊) that is traditionally a dessert in East Asian and Southeast Asian cultures. Over the years, we got feedback that it was too heavy as a beverage so we thinned out our recipe a bit.

Our housemade black sesame paste is a combination of the black sesame seed itself along with ginger and some brown sugar. Black sesame is known to improve circulation and provide an anti-oxidant boost. (📸: @christophertestani @thebobabook)

Today, we finally launched our community platform called Boba Guys Passport (as announced in Amsterdam). We didn’t want to do a fancy press release for this and instead want to give you a deep cut back story.

We almost lost it all during the pandemic. We were buried under immense debt (like so many businesses coming out of Covid) and one of our secret weapons— our vertically-integrated supply chain— was crippled by the global logistics challenges. And despite what the internet says, we do not have a venture capital / private equity backstop. Boba Guys lasted for over a decade because of you, our community.

We said that if we survive, we would figure out a way to bridge our community. Many of you know our mission is to bridge cultures, but few know that it was always an ideological battle. We’d say, “from East to West, old and young, Team Edward to Team Jacob” (sorry for the outdated Twilight reference).

So today marks the beginning of our Run It Back strategy where we reassert our roots of innovation, community, and radical candor. We’ve been diligently working behind the scenes building the foundation of what we believe is the future of omnichannel retail businesses like ours. Kudos to my cofounder @ymfy, Hang.xyz, and @solana for building the platform for the next generation. We hesitate to call it a loyalty program as it’s much more— it is our community engagement platform. We are known for our intimate connection with our guests, so aside from collecting points from purchases, Passport is how we will make local announcements and giveaway some of the signature perks that made us who we are today.

And yes, it all began with the 800+ of you who piloted our physical Passport program. You followed the white rabbit and found the Easter eggs. You helped bring this all to life. 

And for businesses out there who feel old, discouraged, or exhausted, hang in there. You will survive, the spark will come back, and you’ll run it back, too. So yeah, a boba shop launching this next gen tech? What a world, right? 🙏🏼🫡
